{"title_page": "AJ Ginnis", "text_new": "{{Infobox alpine ski racer\n| name           = AJ Ginnis\n| image          = [[File:Aj ginnis|thumb]]\n| disciplines    = [[Slalom skiing|Slalom]], [[Giant slalom]]\n| club           = [[Green Mountain Valley School]]\n| birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1994|11|17|df=y}}\n| birth_place    = [[Athens]], [[Greece]]\n| height          = 6' , 182 cm\n| wcdebut        = {{aligned table|leftright=y|fullwidth=y|class=nowrap| 22 December [[2015 Alpine Skiing World Cup|2014]] (age 20)|}}\n| worldsteams    = 8\n| worldsmedals   = 1\n| wcseasons      = 5rd \u2013 ([[2015 Alpine Skiing World Cup|2015]]\u2013)\n| show-medals    = yes\n}}\n\n'''AJ Ginnis''' (born 17 November 1994)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://data.fis-ski.com/dynamic/athlete-biography.html?sector=AL&listid=&competitorid=161182&type=result|title=FIS profile|publisher=Fis-ski.com|accessdate=23 December 2016}}</ref> is a Greek-American [[Alpine skiing|alpine ski racer]]. Ginnis specializes in the technical events of [[Slalom skiing|Slalom]] and [[Giant slalom]]. Ginnis made his World Cup debut on 22 December [[2015 Alpine Skiing World Cup|2014]].\n\n==Early life==\nBorn in [[Athens]], [[Greece]], Ginnis grew up in [[Vouliagmeni]]. He started skiing at Parnassos Mountain at the age of 2. His father ran a ski school. He moved to [[Austria]] before moving to Vermont's famed [[Green Mountain Valley School]] , where he started to fine-tune his skiing.<ref>[http://alpine.usskiteam.com/athletes/aj-ginnis AJ Ginnis | U.S. Ski Team - Alpine]</ref>\n==Career==\nGinnis was named to the US Ski Team in the spring of 2012 at the age of 17. After tearing his ACL that following season he was able to climb the ranks and make his World Cup debut on 22 December [[2015 Alpine Skiing World Cup|2014]] in the [[Madonna di Campiglio]] [[Slalom skiing|Slalom]]. That same season Ginnis won the Bronze Medal in the Slalom at the World Junior Championships in Hafjel, Norway and continued to climb the ranks by securing podiums at the European - Cup, North American - Cup, and National Championship events. During the 2016 - 2017 season Ginnis qualified to represent Team USA at the 2017 Alpine World Championships hosted by St. Moritz, Switzerland.second run.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://medias3.fis-ski.com/pdf/2015/AL/0149/2015AL0149RLR1.pdf|title=Men's Slalom - Madonna di Campiglio (ITA) - 1st Run|accessdate=22 December 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://medias1.fis-ski.com/pdf/2015/AL/0149/2015AL0149RLR2.pdf|title=Men's Slalom - Madonna di Campiglio (ITA) - Official Results|accessdate=22 December 2014}}</ref> On 22 December 2016 he scored his first World Cup points finishing 13th in the [[Madonna di Campiglio]] [[Slalom skiing|Slalom]]. Ginnis' career has been plagued by injuries as he has received more than 5 surgeries on the same knee. Knee injuries kept him sidelined during the 2018 and 2019 seasons. In the 2020 season Ginnis raced for Dartmouth College while re qualifying for the US's World Cup team. \n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{FIS alpine skier|161182}}\n* [http://data.fis-ski.com/dynamic/athlete-biography.html?sector=AL&competitorid=161182&type=st-WC FIS-ski.com] \u2013 AJ Ginnis \u2013 World Cup season standings\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ginnis, AJ}}\n[[Category:1994 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American male alpine skiers]]\n[[Category:Greek male alpine skiers]]\n\n\n{{Greece-alpine-skiing-bio-stub}}\n[[File:AJ Ginnis.png|thumb|AJ Ginnis ]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox alpine ski racer\n| name           = AJ Ginnis\n| disciplines    = [[Slalom skiing|Slalom]], [[Giant slalom]]\n| club           = [[Green Mountain Valley School]]\n| birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1994|11|17|df=y}}\n| birth_place    = [[Athens]], [[Greece]]\n| height          = 6' , 182 cm\n| wcdebut        = {{aligned table|leftright=y|fullwidth=y|class=nowrap| 22 December [[2015 Alpine Skiing World Cup|2014]] (age 20)|}}\n| worldsteams    = 8\n| worldsmedals   = 1\n| wcseasons      = 5rd \u2013 ([[2015 Alpine Skiing World Cup|2015]]\u2013)\n| show-medals    = yes\n}}\n\n'''AJ Ginnis''' (born 17 November 1994)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://data.fis-ski.com/dynamic/athlete-biography.html?sector=AL&listid=&competitorid=161182&type=result|title=FIS profile|publisher=Fis-ski.com|accessdate=23 December 2016}}</ref> is a Greek-American [[Alpine skiing|alpine ski racer]]. Ginnis specializes in the technical events of [[Slalom skiing|Slalom]] and [[Giant slalom]]. Ginnis made his World Cup debut on 22 December [[2015 Alpine Skiing World Cup|2014]].\n\n==Early life==\nBorn in [[Athens]], [[Greece]], Ginnis grew up in [[Vouliagmeni]]. He started skiing at Parnassos Mountain at the age of 2. His father ran a ski school. He moved to [[Austria]] before moving to Vermont's famed [[Green Mountain Valley School]] , where he started to fine-tune his skiing.<ref>[http://alpine.usskiteam.com/athletes/aj-ginnis AJ Ginnis | U.S. Ski Team - Alpine]</ref>\n\n==Career==\nGinnis was named to the US Ski Team in the spring of 2012 at the age of 17. After tearing his ACL that following season he was able to climb the ranks and make his World Cup debut on 22 December [[2015 Alpine Skiing World Cup|2014]] in the [[Madonna di Campiglio]] [[Slalom skiing|Slalom]]. That same season Ginnis won the Bronze Medal in the Slalom at the World Junior Championships in Hafjel, Norway and continued to climb the ranks by securing podiums at the European - Cup, North American - Cup, and National Championship events. During the 2016 - 2017 season Ginnis qualified to represent Team USA at the 2017 Alpine World Championships hosted by St. Moritz, Switzerland.second run.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://medias3.fis-ski.com/pdf/2015/AL/0149/2015AL0149RLR1.pdf|title=Men's Slalom - Madonna di Campiglio (ITA) - 1st Run|accessdate=22 December 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://medias1.fis-ski.com/pdf/2015/AL/0149/2015AL0149RLR2.pdf|title=Men's Slalom - Madonna di Campiglio (ITA) - Official Results|accessdate=22 December 2014}}</ref> On 22 December 2016 he scored his first World Cup points finishing 13th in the [[Madonna di Campiglio]] [[Slalom skiing|Slalom]]. Ginnis' career has been plagued by injuries as he has received more than 5 surgeries on the same knee. Knee injuries kept him sidelined during the 2018 and 2019 seasons. In the 2020 season Ginnis raced for Dartmouth College while re qualifying for the US's World Cup team. \n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{FIS alpine skier|161182}}\n* [http://data.fis-ski.com/dynamic/athlete-biography.html?sector=AL&competitorid=161182&type=st-WC FIS-ski.com] \u2013 AJ Ginnis \u2013 World Cup season standings\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ginnis, AJ}}\n[[Category:1994 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American male alpine skiers]]\n[[Category:Greek male alpine skiers]]\n\n\n{{Greece-alpine-skiing-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Skifanhellas", "label": "safe", "comment": "PIcture", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/AJ_Ginnis"}
{"title_page": "Wheeler School", "text_new": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{COI|date=June 2010}}\n{{Refimprove|date=June 2010}}\n}}\n{{Infobox school\n|name = Wheeler School\n|image = Wheeler2011nightshot.jpg\n|established = {{Start date|1889}}\n|type = [[Private school|Private]]\n|ceeb = 400170\n|us_nces_school_id = Wheeler: {{NCES Private School ID|01258081|school_name=Wheeler School|access_date=Oct 22, 2014}}<br />Hamilton: {{NCES Private School ID|A9300828|school_name=Hamilton School At Wheeler|ref_name=\"hamilton\"|access_date=Oct 22, 2014}}\n|head_name = Head of School\n|head = Allison Gaines Pell\n|address  = 216 Hope Street\n|city = [[Providence, Rhode Island|Providence]]\n|state = [[Rhode Island]]\n|zipcode = 02906\n|country = [[United States]]\n|coordinates={{Coord|41.828954|-71.397875|format=dms|display=inline,title}}\n|campus_type = Urban, {{convert|12|acre|ha}}<br />Farm, {{convert|120|acre|ha}}\n|enrollment = Wheeler: 788<ref name=\"nces_psch\" /><br />Hamilton: 72<ref name=\"hamilton\" />\n|faculty = Wheeler: 123<ref name=\"nces_psch\" /><br />Hamilton 16.3<ref name=\"hamilton\" />\n|class =\n|ratio = 6.2:1\n|accreditation = [[National Association of Independent Schools|NAIS]]<ref name=\"nces_psch\" />\n|SAT = 680 [Math] 660 [Reading] 690 [Writing] 2030 [Composite]<ref>{{cite web|title=Explore Wheeler School|url=https://www.niche.com/k12/wheeler-school-providence-ri/|website=Niche|accessdate=June 15, 2017}}</ref>\n|athletics = SENE and Rhode Island Interscholastic League\n|colors = {{Color box|#3a0184|border=darkgray}} Purple<br />{{Color box|#fdc20e|border=darkgray}} Gold\n|motto  = '''''The Spirit Giveth Life'''''\n|mascot = The Warrior\n|homepage = {{url|http://www.wheelerschool.org}}\n|yearbook = Gyre}}\n[[File:The Wheeler School, Providence RI.jpg|thumb|right]]\n'''The Wheeler School''' is a [[coeducation]]al independent day school located on the East Side of [[Providence, Rhode Island|Providence]], [[Rhode Island]], U. S. The school serves students from the nursery level through twelfth-grade.<ref name=\"Website\">{{cite web|title=Wheeler School ~ History of the School|url=https://www.wheelerschool.org/podium/default.aspx?t=112097&rc=0|website=www.wheelerschool.org|accessdate=June 15, 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110728175030/https://www.wheelerschool.org/podium/default.aspx?t=112097&rc=0|archivedate=July 28, 2011|date=28 July 2011}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n=== Mary C. Wheeler ===\nSchool founder, [[Mary Colman Wheeler]] was born in [[Concord, Massachusetts]], on May 15, 1846. She graduated from [[Concord-Carlisle High School|Concord High School]] and [[Abbot Academy]] in [[Andover, Massachusetts|Andover]], Massachusetts. She began her educational career teaching mathematics and Latin in the Concord school system. In 1868, she moved to [[Providence, Rhode Island|Providence]], Rhode Island to teach at Miss Shaw's, a [[finishing school]] for young ladies. In the 1870s, Wheeler twice traveled to Europe to study art and painting, and between her trips enrolled in a variety of art history courses taught by [[Brown University]] professors. In 1882, she opened an art studio in the Waterman Building on North Main Street in Providence. Two years later, she moved into a house and studio she built at 24 Cabot Street and began to offer painting classes for young women three days a week, and for children on Saturdays. In addition, she held an evening lecture series on Greek literature and early American history.<ref name=\"Website\" />\n\nIn 1887, Wheeler took a group of young women to [[Giverny]], France for a summer of painting, art history and French. These trips were repeated many times through the next two decades and link Wheeler to a number of American Impressionist artists as well as French Impressionist [[Claude Monet]].<ref name=\"Website\" />\n\n=== Early history ===\nIn 1900, adding an academic college preparatory curriculum to her art instruction, Mary Wheeler accepted ten female students as boarders and officially founded The Mary C. Wheeler School. A building on Brook Street was purchased, in 1898, to house girls enrolled in the preparatory program for her Cabot Street School.<ref name=\"Website\" />\n\nIn 1910, Hope Building was constructed to provide living and dining facilities required by a growing student body and faculty. In 1912, the original Fresh Air Building was completed, though it was later rebuilt. The Mary C. Wheeler School thus became one of the first American schools to use the principles of [[Maria Montessori]] in its kindergarten instruction. Wheeler also purchased the Froebel Kindergarten School which admitted boys into its pre-primary grades until the 1950s.<ref name=\"Website\" />\n\nThe daughter of a farmer, Wheeler acquired a {{convert|78|acre|ha|sing=on}} farm and house in [[Seekonk, Massachusetts]] in 1912\u201313. She subsequently purchased an adjoining farm and buildings, bringing the total land holdings to slightly more than {{convert|120|acre|ha}}. At one point, she advertised her school in ''[[Vogue (magazine)|Vogue]]'' as the Mary C. Wheeler Town & Country School.<ref name=\"Website\" />\n\nMary Helena Dey was hired in 1914 to reorder the school\u2019s curriculum. As a result, the school became a pioneer in the educational theories of [[John Dewey]]. Through Dey\u2019s contacts, such notables as [[Carl Sandburg]] came to campus to meet with students or, in Sandburg\u2019s case, deliver the graduation address.<ref name=\"Website\" />\n\nThe first Wheeler Field Day was celebrated in 1915, and is the oldest continuously-celebrated tradition at the school.<ref name=\"Website\" />\n\n=== Middle years: 1920-1980 ===\nWheeler died in 1920 at the age of 73. In her will she established a [[Board of Trustees|board of trustees]] to oversee the school. Mary Helena Dey, who had studied under educational theorist John Dewey at the [[University of Chicago]], was named headmistress. In the mid-20s, the farm facilities were expanded at a cost of $4,400 to include a field hockey field and two tennis courts. The \u201cswimming hole\u201d was enlarged and deepened. Later an [[arboretum]], featuring several hundred unusual plants and trees, was established at the farm in Dey's name, but has been lost to time.<ref name=\"Website\" />\n\nIn 1940, Mabel Van Norman was appointed the third headmistress on the retirement of Dey, Van Norman continued the school through the years of World War II and spent time visiting war-torn schools in the Netherlands and Belgium which Wheeler students helped to support with food and supplies. In 1950, she was succeeded by S. Rowland \u201cRowly\u201d Morgan, Jr.<ref name=\"Website\" />\n\nMorgan became the first male to lead the school and a residence was purchased, at 211 Hope Street, to provide a home outside of the girls' dormitory for his family. In 1952, the Wheeler Annual Fund was established to support the school through donations by alumni, family and friends.<ref name=\"Website\" />\n\nIn 1968, Hugh A. Madden was named headmaster. Coeducation was approved for the lower grades in 1973, and expanded to include the entire school in 1975. The name of the school officially changed to The Wheeler School. The boarding program was phased out in 1979.\n\n=== Modern-era ===\n[[File:Wheeler School Gilder Center for Performing Arts.jpg|thumb|right|Gilder Center for the Performing Arts and Prescott Library]]\nWilliam C. Prescott, Jr. succeeded Hugh Madden as headmaster in 1980.<ref name=\"Website\" />\n\nThe Hamilton School at Wheeler opened in 1988 to its first group of 35 students in grades 1-6.<ref name=\"Website\" /> In 1990, a new library was constructed. The building  was designed by Schwartz/Silver Architects of Boston. A large division of the library is named in memory of third headmistress Mabel Van Norman.<ref name=\"Website\" />\n\nWheeler was the Providence site of the [[Breakthrough Collaborative|Summerbridge National]] program in 1992.<ref name=\"Website\" />\n\n[[WELH|WELH-FM]] (Wheeler's radio station at FM 88.1) went on the air in 1994 at the end of a 10-year process begun as an Aerie{{Clarify|reason=what is this?|date=June 2017}} student project. As of 2006, the station broadcasts Spanish-language programming in the morning and a [[Oldies|golden oldies]] format in the afternoon, and the station streams via the internet. Students also use the facilities to record news programs and interviews.<ref name=\"Website\" /> Since October 8, 2011, WELH has broadcast programming from [[Rhode Island Public Radio]].<ref name=projo-welhripr>{{cite news|last=Ziner|first=Karen Lee|title=R.I. Latino radio station going 24/7 in new place|url=http://www.projo.com/news/content/LATINO_PUBLIC_RADIO_10-07-11_R4QO3C9_v29.70439.html|accessdate=October 10, 2011|newspaper=[[The Providence Journal]]|date=October 7, 2011}}</ref>\n\nAs of October 2014 the school{{when|date=October 2014}} has nearly 800 students<ref>{{cite web|title=The Wheeler School {{!}} Head of School Dan Miller {{!}} The Wheeler School, Providence RI|url=https://www.wheelerschool.org/page/about-wheeler/head-of-schools-welcome|website=www.wheelerschool.org|accessdate=June 15, 2017|language=en}}</ref> with 200 faculty and staff. In addition to its main campus in Providence, the school has a {{convert|120|acre|ha|sing=on}} farm facility for athletics, the Sixth Grade Farm Program, summer camp, ropes course, sports programs and environmental research.\n\nIn 2014 the school dedicated a new 18,000 square foot performing arts center featuring a stepped seating auditorium, five new performing arts classrooms, studios, and storage spaces.<ref>{{cite web |title=The Wheeler School, Gilder Center for Performing Arts |url=https://www.odehengineers.com/Project/Wheeler-Gilder |website=Odeh Engineers |publisher=Odeh Engineers |accessdate=31 August 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Notable alumni ==\n{{alumni|date=March 2018}}\n* [[Devere Allen]] (1891-1955) - [[Pacifism|pacifist]] journalist and political activist, editor of ''[[The World Tomorrow (magazine)|The World Tomorrow]]'' magazine.\n* [[Scott Carney]] (b. 1978) -  American investigative journalist <ref>[https://www.wheelerschool.org/list-detail?pk=112305&fromId=239966]</ref>\n* [[Trudy Coxe]] (b. 1949) - CEO of the [[Preservation Society of Newport County]] and former Environmental Secretary of Massachusetts.\n* [[Nico Muhly]] (b. 1981) - contemporary classical music composer.\n* [[John Brandt]] (b. 1987) - Amateur recruiter and professional Gumby impersonator.\n* [[Josh Schwartz]] (b. 1976) - writer/producer of the television series ''[[The O.C.]]'', ''[[Chuck (TV series)|Chuck]]'', ''[[Gossip Girl (TV series)|Gossip Girl]]'', and ''[[Hart of Dixie]]''\n* [[Gloria Vanderbilt]] (1924-2019) - American artist, author, actress, fashion designer, heiress, and socialite.\n{{commonscat|The Wheeler School (Providence, Rhode Island)}}\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Private high schools in Rhode Island]]\n[[Category:Private elementary schools in Rhode Island]]\n[[Category:Private middle schools in Rhode Island]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1889]]\n[[Category:High schools in Providence, Rhode Island]]\n[[Category:1889 establishments in Rhode Island]]\n", "text_old": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{COI|date=June 2010}}\n{{Refimprove|date=June 2010}}\n}}\n{{Infobox school\n|name = Wheeler School\n|image = Wheeler2011nightshot.jpg\n|established = {{Start date|1889}}\n|type = [[Private school|Private]]\n|ceeb = 400170\n|us_nces_school_id = Wheeler: {{NCES Private School ID|01258081|school_name=Wheeler School|access_date=Oct 22, 2014}}<br />Hamilton: {{NCES Private School ID|A9300828|school_name=Hamilton School At Wheeler|ref_name=\"hamilton\"|access_date=Oct 22, 2014}}\n|head_name = Head of School\n|head = Allison Gaines Pell\n|address  = 216 Hope Street\n|city = [[Providence, Rhode Island|Providence]]\n|state = [[Rhode Island]]\n|zipcode = 02906\n|country = [[United States]]\n|coordinates={{Coord|41.828954|-71.397875|format=dms|display=inline,title}}\n|campus_type = Urban, {{convert|12|acre|ha}}<br />Farm, {{convert|120|acre|ha}}\n|enrollment = Wheeler: 788<ref name=\"nces_psch\" /><br />Hamilton: 72<ref name=\"hamilton\" />\n|faculty = Wheeler: 123<ref name=\"nces_psch\" /><br />Hamilton 16.3<ref name=\"hamilton\" />\n|class =\n|ratio = 6.2:1\n|accreditation = [[National Association of Independent Schools|NAIS]]<ref name=\"nces_psch\" />\n|SAT = 680 [Math] 660 [Reading] 690 [Writing] 2030 [Composite]<ref>{{cite web|title=Explore Wheeler School|url=https://www.niche.com/k12/wheeler-school-providence-ri/|website=Niche|accessdate=June 15, 2017}}</ref>\n|athletics = SENE and Rhode Island Interscholastic League\n|colors = {{Color box|#3a0184|border=darkgray}} Purple<br />{{Color box|#fdc20e|border=darkgray}} Gold\n|motto  = '''''The Spirit Giveth Life'''''\n|mascot = The Warrior\n|homepage = {{url|http://www.wheelerschool.org}}\n|yearbook = Gyre}}\n[[File:The Wheeler School, Providence RI.jpg|thumb|right]]\n'''The Wheeler School''' is a [[coeducation]]al independent day school located on the East Side of [[Providence, Rhode Island|Providence]], [[Rhode Island]], U. S. The school serves students from the nursery level through twelfth-grade.<ref name=\"Website\">{{cite web|title=Wheeler School ~ History of the School|url=https://www.wheelerschool.org/podium/default.aspx?t=112097&rc=0|website=www.wheelerschool.org|accessdate=June 15, 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110728175030/https://www.wheelerschool.org/podium/default.aspx?t=112097&rc=0|archivedate=July 28, 2011|date=28 July 2011}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n=== Mary C. Wheeler ===\nSchool founder, [[Mary Colman Wheeler]] was born in [[Concord, Massachusetts]], on May 15, 1846. She graduated from [[Concord-Carlisle High School|Concord High School]] and [[Abbot Academy]] in [[Andover, Massachusetts|Andover]], Massachusetts. She began her educational career teaching mathematics and Latin in the Concord school system. In 1868, she moved to [[Providence, Rhode Island|Providence]], Rhode Island to teach at Miss Shaw's, a [[finishing school]] for young ladies. In the 1870s, Wheeler twice traveled to Europe to study art and painting, and between her trips enrolled in a variety of art history courses taught by [[Brown University]] professors. In 1882, she opened an art studio in the Waterman Building on North Main Street in Providence. Two years later, she moved into a house and studio she built at 24 Cabot Street and began to offer painting classes for young women three days a week, and for children on Saturdays. In addition, she held an evening lecture series on Greek literature and early American history.<ref name=\"Website\" />\n\nIn 1887, Wheeler took a group of young women to [[Giverny]], France for a summer of painting, art history and French. These trips were repeated many times through the next two decades and link Wheeler to a number of American Impressionist artists as well as French Impressionist [[Claude Monet]].<ref name=\"Website\" />\n\n=== Early history ===\nIn 1900, adding an academic college preparatory curriculum to her art instruction, Mary Wheeler accepted ten female students as boarders and officially founded The Mary C. Wheeler School. A building on Brook Street was purchased, in 1898, to house girls enrolled in the preparatory program for her Cabot Street School.<ref name=\"Website\" />\n\nIn 1910, Hope Building was constructed to provide living and dining facilities required by a growing student body and faculty. In 1912, the original Fresh Air Building was completed, though it was later rebuilt. The Mary C. Wheeler School thus became one of the first American schools to use the principles of [[Maria Montessori]] in its kindergarten instruction. Wheeler also purchased the Froebel Kindergarten School which admitted boys into its pre-primary grades until the 1950s.<ref name=\"Website\" />\n\nThe daughter of a farmer, Wheeler acquired a {{convert|78|acre|ha|sing=on}} farm and house in [[Seekonk, Massachusetts]] in 1912\u201313. She subsequently purchased an adjoining farm and buildings, bringing the total land holdings to slightly more than {{convert|120|acre|ha}}. At one point, she advertised her school in ''[[Vogue (magazine)|Vogue]]'' as the Mary C. Wheeler Town & Country School.<ref name=\"Website\" />\n\nMary Helena Dey was hired in 1914 to reorder the school\u2019s curriculum. As a result, the school became a pioneer in the educational theories of [[John Dewey]]. Through Dey\u2019s contacts, such notables as [[Carl Sandburg]] came to campus to meet with students or, in Sandburg\u2019s case, deliver the graduation address.<ref name=\"Website\" />\n\nThe first Wheeler Field Day was celebrated in 1915, and is the oldest continuously-celebrated tradition at the school.<ref name=\"Website\" />\n\n=== Middle years: 1920-1980 ===\nWheeler died in 1920 at the age of 73. In her will she established a [[Board of Trustees|board of trustees]] to oversee the school. Mary Helena Dey, who had studied under educational theorist John Dewey at the [[University of Chicago]], was named headmistress. In the mid-20s, the farm facilities were expanded at a cost of $4,400 to include a field hockey field and two tennis courts. The \u201cswimming hole\u201d was enlarged and deepened. Later an [[arboretum]], featuring several hundred unusual plants and trees, was established at the farm in Dey's name, but has been lost to time.<ref name=\"Website\" />\n\nIn 1940, Mabel Van Norman was appointed the third headmistress on the retirement of Dey, Van Norman continued the school through the years of World War II and spent time visiting war-torn schools in the Netherlands and Belgium which Wheeler students helped to support with food and supplies. In 1950, she was succeeded by S. Rowland \u201cRowly\u201d Morgan, Jr.<ref name=\"Website\" />\n\nMorgan became the first male to lead the school and a residence was purchased, at 211 Hope Street, to provide a home outside of the girls' dormitory for his family. In 1952, the Wheeler Annual Fund was established to support the school through donations by alumni, family and friends.<ref name=\"Website\" />\n\nIn 1968, Hugh A. Madden was named headmaster. Coeducation was approved for the lower grades in 1973, and expanded to include the entire school in 1975. The name of the school officially changed to The Wheeler School. The boarding program was phased out in 1979.\n\n=== Modern-era ===\n[[File:Wheeler School Gilder Center for Performing Arts.jpg|thumb|right|Gilder Center for the Performing Arts and Prescott Library]]\nWilliam C. Prescott, Jr. succeeded Hugh Madden as headmaster in 1980.<ref name=\"Website\" />\n\nThe Hamilton School at Wheeler opened in 1988 to its first group of 35 students in grades 1-6.<ref name=\"Website\" /> In 1990, a new library was constructed. The building  was designed by Schwartz/Silver Architects of Boston. A large division of the library is named in memory of third headmistress Mabel Van Norman.<ref name=\"Website\" />\n\nWheeler was the Providence site of the [[Breakthrough Collaborative|Summerbridge National]] program in 1992.<ref name=\"Website\" />\n\n[[WELH|WELH-FM]] (Wheeler's radio station at FM 88.1) went on the air in 1994 at the end of a 10-year process begun as an Aerie{{Clarify|reason=what is this?|date=June 2017}} student project. As of 2006, the station broadcasts Spanish-language programming in the morning and a [[Oldies|golden oldies]] format in the afternoon, and the station streams via the internet. Students also use the facilities to record news programs and interviews.<ref name=\"Website\" /> Since October 8, 2011, WELH has broadcast programming from [[Rhode Island Public Radio]].<ref name=projo-welhripr>{{cite news|last=Ziner|first=Karen Lee|title=R.I. Latino radio station going 24/7 in new place|url=http://www.projo.com/news/content/LATINO_PUBLIC_RADIO_10-07-11_R4QO3C9_v29.70439.html|accessdate=October 10, 2011|newspaper=[[The Providence Journal]]|date=October 7, 2011}}</ref>\n\nAs of October 2014 the school{{when|date=October 2014}} has nearly 800 students<ref>{{cite web|title=The Wheeler School {{!}} Head of School Dan Miller {{!}} The Wheeler School, Providence RI|url=https://www.wheelerschool.org/page/about-wheeler/head-of-schools-welcome|website=www.wheelerschool.org|accessdate=June 15, 2017|language=en}}</ref> with 200 faculty and staff. In addition to its main campus in Providence, the school has a {{convert|120|acre|ha|sing=on}} farm facility for athletics, the Sixth Grade Farm Program, summer camp, ropes course, sports programs and environmental research.\n\nIn 2014 the school dedicated a new 18,000 square foot performing arts center featuring a stepped seating auditorium, five new performing arts classrooms, studios, and storage spaces.<ref>{{cite web |title=The Wheeler School, Gilder Center for Performing Arts |url=https://www.odehengineers.com/Project/Wheeler-Gilder |website=Odeh Engineers |publisher=Odeh Engineers |accessdate=31 August 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Notable alumni ==\n{{alumni|date=March 2018}}\n* [[Devere Allen]] (1891-1955) - [[Pacifism|pacifist]] journalist and political activist, editor of ''[[The World Tomorrow (magazine)|The World Tomorrow]]'' magazine.\n* [[Scott Carney]] (b. 1978) -  American investigative journalist <ref>[https://www.wheelerschool.org/list-detail?pk=112305&fromId=239966]</ref>\n* [[Trudy Coxe]] (b. 1949) - CEO of the [[Preservation Society of Newport County]] and former Environmental Secretary of Massachusetts.\n* [[Nico Muhly]] (b. 1981) - contemporary classical music composer.\n* [[Josh Schwartz]] (b. 1976) - writer/producer of the television series ''[[The O.C.]]'', ''[[Chuck (TV series)|Chuck]]'', ''[[Gossip Girl (TV series)|Gossip Girl]]'', and ''[[Hart of Dixie]]''\n* [[Gloria Vanderbilt]] (1924-2019) - American artist, author, actress, fashion designer, heiress, and socialite.\n{{commonscat|The Wheeler School (Providence, Rhode Island)}}\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Private high schools in Rhode Island]]\n[[Category:Private elementary schools in Rhode Island]]\n[[Category:Private middle schools in Rhode Island]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1889]]\n[[Category:High schools in Providence, Rhode Island]]\n[[Category:1889 establishments in Rhode Island]]\n", "name_user": "24.61.20.41", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wheeler_School"}
{"title_page": "Political parties and political designations in Massachusetts", "text_new": "In the [[Commonwealth of Massachusetts]] (a [[U.S. state]]), there are four recognized '''political parties''' and an additional 25 '''political designations''' in which [[Voter registration in the United States|registered voters]] may choose to enroll. Voters may also choose to remain as \"[[unenrolled voter]]s\" (i.e., [[Independent (voter)|independents]]). [[List of political parties in the United States|Political parties]] hold [[primary election]]s, while political designations do not. A political designation is a one-to-three word descriptive term which may appear next to candidates' names on election ballots. To be recognized as a political designation, fifty registered voters must file a document with the state seeking this status.\n\n==Background==\nIn Massachusetts, election ballots include the candidates' names followed by either the candidates' party or his or her \"political designation\"&mdash;a one-to-three word description that must be another one-to-three word term whose recognition has been requested by fifty or more registered voters. In many cases, non-party designations include the word \"party\" in the designation. However, only four such designations actually correspond to organizations that are recognized by Massachusetts as political parties: the [[Massachusetts Republican Party|Republican Party]], the [[Massachusetts Democratic Party|Democratic Party]], the [[Libertarian Party of Massachusetts|Libertarian Party]], and the [[Green-Rainbow Party]].\n\n==Enrolled and unenrolled voters==\nIn Massachusetts, [[Voter registration in the United States|registered voters]] may choose to (1) enroll in a political party; (2) enroll with a political designation; or (3) choose to be an [[unenrolled voter]] (i.e., an [[independent (voter)|independent]]).<ref name=\"sos\"/><ref name=\"Rhodes\">{{cite news|last1=Rhodes|first1=George|title=In Mass., there's even a Pizza Party|url=http://www.thesunchronicle.com/vip/opinion/columns/rhodes-in-mass-there-s-even-a-pizza-party/article_50ca637a-3cb1-11e5-bdda-e7cb96441501.html|accessdate=8 August 2016|work=Sun Chronicle|date=6 August 2015}}</ref>\n\nVoters may change their enrollment status with their election official, with a deadline twenty days before an election.<ref name=\"sos\"/>\n\nAll registered voters may vote in general elections. Massachusetts voters enrolled in a particular party may vote only in that party's [[Primary elections|primary]], and cannot cross-over to vote in another party's primary,<ref name=\"sos\"/> but \"unenrolled\" voters may cast a primary ballot for one of the four parties.<ref name=\"NReading\">[http://www.northreadingma.gov/town-clerk/pages/political-parties-and-political-designations Political Parties and Political Designations, As of 12/31/2014], Town of North Reading (accessed August 27, 2016).</ref><ref>[http://www.ncsl.org/research/elections-and-campaigns/primary-types.aspx State Primary Election Types], [[National Conference of State Legislatures]] (July 21, 2016).</ref> Political designations are treated as \"unenrolled\" voters for primary purposes, and so they too may choose to vote in one of the party primaries.<ref name=\"NReading\"/>\n\nUnder Massachusetts law, a political designation is created when fifty registered Massachusetts voters \"file a form with the [[Secretary of the Commonwealth of Massachusetts|Secretary of the Commonwealth]] requesting that they, or any other voters, may change their registration to such designation.\"<ref>[https://www.cityofboston.gov/elections/vote/faq.asp Frequently Asked Questions for New Voters], City of Boston Election Department (accessed August 27, 2016).</ref> These non-party political designations may field candidates for statewide office, if they petition with a sufficient number of signatures (10,000).<ref>{{cite news|last1=Winger|first1=Richard|title=Libertarian Petition in Massachusetts Has Enough Valid Signatures|url=http://ballot-access.org/2016/08/08/libertarian-petition-in-massachusetts-has-enough-valid-signatures/|accessdate=8 August 2016|work=[[Ballot Access News]]|date=8 August 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe various political designations have generally small membership, although they have attracted some media attention.<ref name=\"wm\">{{cite news|last1=Quinn|first1=Tom|title=Tired of politics as usual? Tap your inner pirate, or try pizza|url=http://worcestermag.com/2016/04/14/tired-politics-usual-tap-inner-pirate-try-pizza/41940|accessdate=8 August 2016|work=[[Worcester Magazine]]|date=14 April 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Rhodes\"/>\n\n==List of current parties and designations==\nAs of 2019, the [[Secretary of the Commonwealth of Massachusetts|Secretary of the Commonwealth]] listed four officially recognized political parties and 26 officially recognized political designations in Massachusetts.<ref name=\"sos\">{{cite web|title=Massachusetts Directory of Political Parties and Designations|url=https://www.sec.state.ma.us/ele/elepar/paridx.htm|website=sec.state.ma.us|publisher=[[Secretary of the Commonwealth of Massachusetts]]|accessdate=October 29, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=Cambridge Election Commission Voter Registration Training Manual|date=2011|publisher=City of Cambridge|location=[[Cambridge, Massachusetts]]|page=5}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Designation !! Abbreviation !! Type !! \n|-\n|{{Party shading/Democratic}} | [[Massachusetts Democratic Party|Democratic Party]]|| D || political party ||\n|-\n|{{Party shading/Republican}} | [[Massachusetts Republican Party|Republican Party]] || R || political party ||\n|-\n|{{Party shading/Libertarian}} | [[Libertarian Party of Massachusetts|Libertarian Party]]|| L || political party ||\n|-\n| {{Party shading/Green}} |[[Green-Rainbow Party]]|| J || political party ||\n|-\n| America First Party || V || non-party political designation ||\n|-\n| [[American Independent Party]] || Q || non-party political designation ||\n|-\n| American Term Limits || BB || non-party political designation ||\n|-\n| Conservative Party || A || non-party political designation ||\n|-\n| {{Party shading/Constitution}} |[[Constitution Party (United States)|Constitution Party]] || K || non-party political designation ||\n|-\n|{{Party shading/Green}} | [[Green Party USA]] || G || non-party political designation || \n|-\n|{{Party shading/Independent}} | Interdependent 3rd Party || T || non-party political designation ||\n|-\n| Latino-Vote Party ||  || non-party political designation ||\n|-\n| Massachusetts Independent Party || O || non-party political designation ||\n|-\n| [[Natural Law Party (United States)|Natural Law Party]] || B || non-party political designation ||\n|-\n| New Alliance Party || N || non-party political designation ||\n|-\n| New England Independence Party || NE || non-party political designation ||\n|-\n| New World Council || C || non-party political designation ||\n|-\n| [[United States Pirate Party|Pirate]] || X || non-party political designation ||\n|-\n| Pizza Party || AA || non-party political designation ||\n|-\n| {{Party shading/Prohibition}} |[[Prohibition Party]] || P || non-party political designation ||\n|-\n| Rainbow Coalition || F || non-party political designation ||\n|-\n|{{Party shading/ReformUSA}} | [[Reform Party of the United States of America|Reform Party]] || E || non-party political designation ||\n|-\n|{{Party shading/Socialist}} | [[Socialist Party of Massachusetts|Socialist]] || S || non-party political designation ||\n|-\n| Timesizing Not Downsizing|| M || non-party political designation ||\n|-\n| Twelve Visions Party||DD|| non-party political designation ||\n|-\n| [[United Independent Party]]||CC|| non-party political designation || \n|-\n| Veterans Party America || W || non-party political designation ||\n|-\n| We The People|| H || non-party political designation ||\n|-\n|{{Party shading/Working Families Party}} | [[Working Families Party|